\begin_layout Section
The Untis System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most daunting problems with Untis stem from the environment which must
 be used to operate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Windows vs.
 The World
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Untis operates solely in a windows environment.
 This is a design choice based upon the use of Untis without the multiuser
 module.
 This choice is based upon two premices: that typically a single individual
 creates the lesson schedules for a school, and that this person is using
 a computer with a Windows OS on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However Untis with activated multiuser module takes away both of those arguement
s.
 Firstly, as the name multiuser implies, it is supposed to be designed to
 be used by multiple users.
 This can occur in three variations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each user installs Untis directly on their computer and Untis communicates
 with a central external databank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each user logs remotely onto the same server where Untis installed.
 Untis then communicates from this server communicates with an internal
 or external the central databank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A combination of the first two.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When multiple users each use an individual computer the chances increase
 greatly that another operating system will be on that computer most notably
 the rather large increase in the use of Macs over the last five or six
 years.
 When multiple users log remotely onto a server, the chances are higher
 to come across a unix/linux server than windows unless the operators of
 the server ........
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
32 vs.
 64 bit Systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Untis, like many programs, operates in a 32 bit environment.
 The multiuser version of Untis also relies on 32 bit ODBC connections.
\end_layout

